Description

Pick samples for the next sequencing run! Maximum = 30 crab stomachs

A reminder of the project goal: > Examine the risk to Dungeness crab instars (age 0+ juveniles) from climate-driven changes in estuarine prey availability.

And a general flowchart for the methods: Describe the current diet of juvenile Dungeness crab -> use existing literature to come up with scenarios of the potential effects of climate change on prey abundance (also, to gather prey energy density info) -> use bioenergetic models to explore the (lack of?) sensitivity of crab instars to climate change impacts on prey availability.

Table 1. Sample sizes for each site.

table-1-img

Tentative plan: Variability in prey species among individual crab and between sites are both high. Individual crab tend to have a high degree of species richness, and I didnt see much saturation in the observed species / families either overall or at individual sites. As a result, I would aim for samples which provide even coverage across the three different bays, and if possible, across habitat types within bays. This would provide a broader diet portfolio that is more generally applicable to the northern Puget Sound maybe resulting in a sensitivity analysis that isnt potentially specific to the prey available at one site? Especially if juveniles are essentially scavengers of whatever is there.

Alternatively, I could max out the samples that I have at 1-2 sites, and try to reach a point of saturation. This could help me explore the degree to which crab in the same location may diversify their diet, justifying low sensitivity by a willingness to switch prey??

  6. saturation point for higher taxonomic levels

distinctness

Taxonomic distinctness = the averaged taxonomic distances among species or individuals in the community (Clarke & Warwick 1998, 2001). In this context, Ill find the distinctness in prey assemblages between crab (with presence/absence data, both distinctness and diversity reduce to the same index, \(\Delta^{+}\), Clarke & Warwick (1998)).

\(\Delta^(+)\) per site:

##       KAY KAY-shell      CLAY     MARPT 
##     96.41     96.26     94.20     90.74


Standard deviation of \(\Delta^(+)\)

##     0.833     1.067     0.721     2.506
